{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Protamines are small, highly basic proteins, that substitute for histones in sperm chromatin during the haploid phase of spermatogenesis. They pack sperm DNA into a highly condensed, stable and inactive complex [[cite:PUB00100028], [cite:PUB00075474]], creating a more hydrodynamic sperm head for efficient swimming and protects the DNA from UV radiation and DNA damage [[cite:PUB00100028], [cite:PUB00075474]]. These proteins bind nonspecifically to the DNA and use a multi-step process to loop the DNA [[cite:PUB00100028]]. There are two different types of mammalian protamine, called P1 and P2. P1 has been found in all species studied, while P2 is sometimes absent [[cite:PUB00075474]]. There seems to be a single type of avian protamine whose sequence is closely related to that of mammalian P1 [[cite:PUB00002517]]. Sequence comparisons of vertebrate and invertebrate protamines show that the sequence, structure, and probably function of these proteins evolve independently in vertebrates and various invertebrate groups [[cite:PUB00075474]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"prosite" {"PS00048" "Protamine P1 signature"}, "pfam" {"PF00260" "Protamine P1"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Protamine P1", "short" "Protamine_P1"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 1, "proteomes" 104, "taxa" 906, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 423, "sets" 0, "proteins" 423, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 343}, "pathways" 1}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"prositedoc" {"displayName" "PROSITE Doc", "description" "PROSITE is a database of protein families and domains.", "rank" 18, "accessions" [{"accession" "PDOC00047", "url" "http://prosite.expasy.org/PDOC00047"}]}}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR000221", :literature {"PUB00002517" {"URL" nil,